---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const title = "From 0 to 80% Test Coverage in 3 Months: A Practical Guide";
const date = "February 28, 2026";
const readTime = "10 min read";

const esc = (s: string) => s.replace(/&/g,'&amp;').replace(/</g,'&lt;').replace(/>/g,'&gt;');

const codeFolderStructure = esc(`tests/
├── auth/
│   ├── login.spec.ts
│   ├── signup.spec.ts
│   ├── password-reset.spec.ts
│   └── session-management.spec.ts
├── checkout/
│   ├── add-to-cart.spec.ts
│   ├── payment-flow.spec.ts
│   ├── subscription-upgrade.spec.ts
│   └── refund-request.spec.ts
├── quests/
│   ├── start-quest.spec.ts
│   ├── complete-quest.spec.ts
│   └── quest-rewards.spec.ts
├── inventory/
│   ├── view-items.spec.ts
│   ├── use-item.spec.ts
│   └── purchase-item.spec.ts
├── pages/
│   ├── LoginPage.ts
│   ├── CheckoutPage.ts
│   ├── QuestPage.ts
│   └── InventoryPage.ts
├── fixtures/
│   ├── auth.ts
│   ├── test-users.ts
│   └── test-data.ts
└── playwright.config.ts`);

const codePlaywrightConfig = esc(`// playwright.config.ts
import { defineConfig, devices } from '@playwright/test';

export default defineConfig({
  testDir: './tests',
  timeout: 30_000,
  retries: process.env.CI ? 2 : 0,
  workers: process.env.CI ? 4 : undefined,
  reporter: [
    ['html', { open: 'never' }],
    ['json', { outputFile: 'test-results/results.json' }],
  ],
  use: {
    baseURL: process.env.BASE_URL || 'http://localhost:3000',
    screenshot: 'only-on-failure',
    trace: 'on-first-retry',
    video: 'on-first-retry',
  },
  projects: [
    {
      name: 'chromium',
      use: { ...devices['Desktop Chrome'] },
    },
    {
      name: 'mobile',
      use: { ...devices['iPhone 14'] },
    },
  ],
});`);

const codePaymentFlow = esc(`// tests/checkout/payment-flow.spec.ts
import { test, expect } from '../../fixtures/auth';
import { CheckoutPage } from '../../pages/CheckoutPage';
import { InventoryPage } from '../../pages/InventoryPage';

test.describe('Payment Flow', () => {
  test('should complete purchase with valid card', async ({
    authenticatedPage: page,
  }) => {
    const inventory = new InventoryPage(page);
    await inventory.navigate();
    await inventory.addItemToCart('Power Boost Pack');

    const checkout = new CheckoutPage(page);
    await checkout.proceedToCheckout();
    await checkout.fillPaymentDetails({
      cardNumber: '4242424242424242',
      expiry: '12/28',
      cvc: '123',
    });
    await checkout.confirmPurchase();

    await expect(checkout.successMessage).toContainText('Purchase complete');
    await expect(checkout.receiptEmail).toBeVisible();
  });

  test('should show error for declined card', async ({
    authenticatedPage: page,
  }) => {
    const inventory = new InventoryPage(page);
    await inventory.navigate();
    await inventory.addItemToCart('Power Boost Pack');

    const checkout = new CheckoutPage(page);
    await checkout.proceedToCheckout();
    await checkout.fillPaymentDetails({
      cardNumber: '4000000000000002', // Stripe test declined card
      expiry: '12/28',
      cvc: '123',
    });
    await checkout.confirmPurchase();

    await expect(checkout.errorMessage).toContainText('declined');
    await expect(checkout.retryButton).toBeVisible();
  });

  test('should preserve cart across page navigation', async ({
    authenticatedPage: page,
  }) => {
    const inventory = new InventoryPage(page);
    await inventory.navigate();
    await inventory.addItemToCart('Power Boost Pack');

    await page.goto('/quests');
    await page.goBack();

    await expect(inventory.cartBadge).toContainText('1');
  });
});`);
---

<BaseLayout locale="en" title={`${title} — Santiago Zapata Mejía`} description="The exact framework, prioritization strategy, and automation patterns I used to achieve 80% E2E test coverage for LingoQuesto in record time.">
  <article class="article">
    <div class="article-container">
      <a href="/en/blog" class="back-link">
        <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none"><path d="M13 8H3M7 4L3 8l4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
        Back to blog
      </a>

      <header class="article-header fade-in">
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span class="article-tag">Tutorial</span>
          <span class="article-date">{date} · {readTime}</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="article-title">{title}</h1>
        <p class="article-subtitle">The exact framework, prioritization strategy, and automation patterns I used to achieve 80% E2E test coverage for LingoQuesto in record time.</p>
      </header>

      <div class="article-body fade-in">
        <p>LingoQuesto is an EdTech platform — language learning through interactive quests. When I came on board, the product was growing fast. New features shipped weekly. And there were exactly zero automated tests.</p>

        <p>The bugs were piling up. Inventory management for in-app items was breaking regularly. The checkout flow — their revenue engine — had intermittent failures that no one could reproduce. Login issues were generating 15+ support tickets per week. The team knew testing was important, but nobody had the bandwidth to start.</p>

        <p>Three months later, we had 80% test coverage of all critical user flows, a CI pipeline that blocked broken code from shipping, and the support ticket volume for technical bugs had dropped by half. Here's how we did it.</p>

        <h2>Weeks 1-2: Identifying What Matters</h2>

        <p>The biggest mistake teams make when starting from zero is trying to test everything. You can't. And if you try, you'll burn out before you see results.</p>

        <p>Instead, I started with a prioritization exercise. I sat down with the product manager, the lead developer, and the support team lead, and we answered one question: <strong>"If this breaks, what hurts the business most?"</strong></p>

        <p>The answer gave us our priority matrix:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Tier 1 (Revenue-critical):</strong> Login/auth, checkout/payment flow, subscription management</li>
          <li><strong>Tier 2 (Core experience):</strong> Quest completion, inventory management, leaderboard updates</li>
          <li><strong>Tier 3 (Important but survivable):</strong> Profile settings, notification preferences, achievement display</li>
          <li><strong>Tier 4 (Nice to have):</strong> Cosmetic features, marketing pages, admin analytics</li>
        </ul>

        <p>This wasn't just about severity — it was about test ROI. Tier 1 tests would catch the bugs that cost real money. Tier 4 tests would catch issues that users might not even notice. We committed to full coverage of Tiers 1 and 2 before touching anything else.</p>

        <p>I also spent this time documenting every critical user flow as a step-by-step script. These manual test scripts became the blueprint for automation — and they were immediately useful to the team for manual regression testing while I built the framework.</p>

        <h2>Weeks 3-4: Building the Foundation</h2>

        <p>With priorities clear, I set up the automation framework. The stack: <strong>Playwright + TypeScript + Page Object Model</strong>. Same approach I've used at DailyBot and other projects, because it works.</p>

        <p>The folder structure followed the business domain, not the technical architecture:</p>

        <pre><code set:html={codeFolderStructure}></code></pre>

        <p>The configuration was optimized for speed and reliability from day one:</p>

        <pre><code set:html={codePlaywrightConfig}></code></pre>

        <p>Key decisions that paid off later:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Retries only in CI.</strong> Locally, a flaky test should fail immediately so you fix it. In CI, a single retry catches genuine environment hiccups.</li>
          <li><strong>Traces and video on first retry.</strong> When a test fails in CI, you get a full recording and trace file. No more "works on my machine" debates.</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile project from day one.</strong> 60% of LingoQuesto's users were on mobile. Testing only desktop would miss their most common experience.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>By the end of week 4, we had 12 tests covering login, signup, and the basic checkout flow. Not a lot — but they were solid, fast (under 2 minutes total), and running on every PR.</p>

        <h2>Month 2: Expanding Coverage Systematically</h2>

        <p>With the foundation in place, month 2 was about volume. I followed a strict pattern for each new test area:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Write the Page Object first.</strong> Define the selectors, interactions, and common assertions for the page. This forces you to think about the page's API before writing test logic.</li>
          <li><strong>Write the happy path test.</strong> User does the thing, thing works. This catches the most common regressions.</li>
          <li><strong>Add error cases.</strong> Invalid input, missing data, unauthorized access. These catch the bugs that slip through because developers test with valid data.</li>
          <li><strong>Add edge cases based on support tickets.</strong> Real-world bugs are better test cases than imagined ones. Every Tier 1/2 support ticket from the last 3 months became a test.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>Here's an example of what a complete checkout test looked like:</p>

        <pre><code set:html={codePaymentFlow}></code></pre>

        <p>By the end of month 2, we had <strong>67 tests</strong> across auth, checkout, quests, and inventory. Coverage of Tier 1 flows was at 95%. Tier 2 was at 60%. Total execution time: 8 minutes in CI with 4 parallel workers.</p>

        <h2>Month 3: CI/CD, Reporting, and Team Onboarding</h2>

        <p>The final month was about making the test suite a permanent part of the development workflow — not just something the QA engineer runs.</p>

        <p><strong>CI/CD integration:</strong> We set up two pipeline stages. A fast "smoke" run (~3 minutes) on every PR that covers auth and checkout. A full regression run (~12 minutes) on merges to the staging branch. Both had to pass before production deploys.</p>

        <p><strong>Reporting:</strong> Playwright's HTML report is good, but the team needed more visibility. I set up a simple dashboard that tracked four metrics over time:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Test coverage %</strong> — how many critical flows are automated (our target: 80%)</li>
          <li><strong>Pass rate</strong> — percentage of tests passing per run (target: >98%)</li>
          <li><strong>Execution time</strong> — how long the suite takes (target: under 15 min for full, under 5 min for smoke)</li>
          <li><strong>Defect escape rate</strong> — how many bugs reach production that tests should have caught (target: under 5%)</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Team onboarding:</strong> I ran two 1-hour workshops for the development team. The first covered how to read test failures and use Playwright's trace viewer. The second covered how to write a test — not because developers should write all the tests, but because they should be able to add a test when fixing a bug.</p>

        <p>I also created a <code>TESTING.md</code> guide in the repo root with:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>How to run tests locally (<code>npm run test:e2e</code>)</li>
          <li>How to run a single test file (<code>npx playwright test tests/auth/login.spec.ts</code>)</li>
          <li>How to debug a failing test (<code>npx playwright test --debug</code>)</li>
          <li>How to add a new Page Object</li>
          <li>Naming conventions and folder structure guide</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The 80/20 Rule of Test Coverage</h2>

        <p>We hit 80% coverage of critical flows by the end of month 3. But let me be clear about what that means — and what it doesn't.</p>

        <p>80% doesn't mean we automated 80% of every possible interaction. It means we automated the 80% of user journeys that generate 95% of the business value. The remaining 20% — edge cases in admin tools, rarely used settings pages, cosmetic interactions — stays manual. And that's fine.</p>

        <p><strong>What to automate:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Revenue-generating flows (checkout, subscriptions, upgrades)</li>
          <li>Authentication and authorization</li>
          <li>Core user journeys (the thing your product actually does)</li>
          <li>Data integrity flows (anything that writes to the database)</li>
          <li>Previously broken things (every production bug becomes a test)</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>What to leave manual:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Highly visual or subjective things (does this animation feel smooth?)</li>
          <li>Rarely used admin features</li>
          <li>One-off marketing pages</li>
          <li>Exploratory edge cases that change frequently</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Final Metrics</h2>

        <p>By the end of the three months:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>87 automated tests</strong> covering auth, checkout, quests, inventory, and API endpoints</li>
          <li><strong>80% critical flow coverage</strong> (Tier 1: 95%, Tier 2: 75%)</li>
          <li><strong>Full suite execution: 12 minutes.</strong> Smoke suite: 3 minutes.</li>
          <li><strong>Defect escape rate dropped from ~18% to ~4%.</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Support tickets for technical bugs dropped 50%</strong></li>
          <li><strong>3 developers</strong> actively contributing tests (up from zero)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Practical Tips for QA Leads Starting from Zero</h2>

        <p><strong>Get executive buy-in with numbers, not feelings.</strong> Before I started, I calculated the cost of bugs: support time, developer time to hotfix, lost revenue from checkout failures. That made the case for investing in automation undeniable.</p>

        <p><strong>Ship your first test in week 1.</strong> Don't spend three weeks setting up the perfect framework. Get a login test running in CI within the first five days. Early wins create momentum and credibility.</p>

        <p><strong>Use the support queue as your test backlog.</strong> Every production bug is a test you should have had. Working backwards from real failures is the fastest way to build a suite that catches real problems.</p>

        <p><strong>Make tests easy to run locally.</strong> If a developer has to configure three environment variables, install Docker, and sacrifice a goat to run tests locally, they won't run them. One command. That's the bar.</p>

        <p><strong>Celebrate the metrics.</strong> Share the dashboard. When defect escape rate drops, tell the team. When the suite catches a bug that would have shipped, post it in Slack. Visibility creates culture change.</p>

        <p><strong>Don't chase 100%.</strong> 80% coverage of the right things beats 100% coverage that takes 45 minutes to run and has 10 flaky tests. The goal isn't a number — it's confidence that the important stuff works.</p>

        <p>Starting from zero is daunting. But it's also an incredible opportunity. You get to design the system right, without legacy baggage. Take it one tier at a time, ship tests early, and let the results compound.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="article-author fade-in">
        <div class="author-info">
          <div class="author-avatar">SZ</div>
          <div>
            <p class="author-name">Santiago Zapata Mejía</p>
            <p class="author-role">QA Automation Lead · Building quality programs for startups</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

